The fix: return the owned value instead of a reference.

Change your function signature from:
```rust
fn build_message() -> &str {
    let buffer = format!("hello {}", name);
    &buffer  // ERROR: buffer is dropped here
}
```

To:
```rust
fn build_message() -> String {
    let buffer = format!("hello {}", name);
    buffer  // OK: ownership moves to the caller
}
```

General rule: accept `&str` in function parameters, return `String` when the function creates new data.

```rust
// Good: accepts &str — works with both String and &str callers
fn greet(name: &str) -> String {
    format!("Hello, {}!", name)
}

// Caller can pass either:
greet("world");                    // &str literal
greet(&my_string);                  // &String auto-derefs to &str
```

Use `String` as a parameter only when the function needs to own the data (e.g., storing it in a struct, sending to another thread, or mutating it).

```rust
struct User {
    name: String,  // owns the data
}

impl User {
    // Takes String because we're storing it
    fn new(name: String) -> Self {
        User { name }
    }
}
```
